%S A396859 7,8,12,13,14,15,16,17,18,19,20,19,19,20,21,22,23,24,23,23
%N A396859 Minimum number of cells in a connected enclosing shell of an n-cell connected hole on the snub-square (3.3.4.3.4) Archimedean tiling.
%C A396859 The snub-square tiling (3.3.4.3.4) is one of the eleven Archimedean tilings of the plane: regular triangles and squares in a 2:1 ratio, with two triangles, a square, a triangle, and a square meeting at every vertex (symmetry group p4g). It is obtained by snubbing the square tiling, that is, rotating each square and filling the gaps with pairs of triangles.
%C A396859 a(n) is the minimum, over all connected holes H of n cells on this tiling, of the number of cells in a connected shell of H. The corona C(H) is the set of cells edge-adjacent to H but not in H; a shell is a connected set of cells, disjoint from H, that contains C(H).
%C A396859 The sequence is not monotonic: a(12) = 19 < a(11) = 20, and a(19) = 23 < a(18) = 24. The corona of a minimizing hole typically splits into several components, so a minimum shell adds bridge cells to connect them; a larger hole can have fewer components and a smaller shell.
%C A396859 For a single hole H the minimum shell size is |C(H)| + 2*v1 + v2 - 2 when v1 >= 1, and |C(H)| + v2 - 1 when v1 = 0 and v2 >= 1, and |C(H)| otherwise, where v1 and v2 count the boundary vertices incident to exactly one and exactly two cells of H.
%C A396859 Conjecture: a(n) - a(n-1) is in {-1, 0, 1} for n >= 4.
%H A396859 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A396859">Paper and figures</a>, GitHub.
%Y A396859 Cf. A394511 (same quantity on the truncated-square (4.8.8) tiling), A395802 (same quantity on the trihexagonal (3.6.3.6) tiling).
